Files Used 
File Name 
books.dat 
issues.dat 
Quit the system safely. 
Purpose 
Stores all book details (binary format). 
Stores records of issued books. 
These files ensure data persistence — meaning data remains saved even after the 
program is closed. 
Important Utility Functions 
Function 
Description 
clear_stdin() Clears leftover input to avoid invalid reads. 
pause_and_clear() Pauses program for user to read output. 
removeNewline() 
Removes newline from fgets() input. 
bookExists() Checks if a book exists by ID. 
updateBookRecord() Updates a specific book record in the file. 
Compilation & Execution 
Save the File 
code.c 
Compile 
gcc code.c -o code 
Run 
./code       
# Linux / Mac 
code.exe     # Windows 
Sample Workflow 
Add a book → e.g. ID=101, Title="C Programming" 
Display all books → confirm it’s added 
Issue the book → enter student name & date 
Return the book → restores quantity 
 
Exit program → data remains stored in .dat files 
 
         Key C Concepts Demonstrated 
 
    Structures 
    File I/O (binary read/write) 
    Menu-driven switch case 
    Function modularity 
    Data persistence 
    Record update/delete logic 
 
      Advantages 
 
Simple and easy to understand 
 
Demonstrates real-world file-based record management 
 
Works on any OS (Windows, Linux, Mac) 
 
No database needed — uses .dat files for storage 
 
      Possible Enhancements 
 
Add student database with unique IDs 
 
Include due dates and fine calculation 
Implement login for admin/librarian 
Add color/clear-screen for better UI 
Convert to GUI or web-based app later 
Conclusion 
The Library Management System in C is a beginner-to-intermediate level project that 
integrates data storage, file handling, and structured programming concepts. 
It effectively simulates a small-scale real-world library operation — a valuable practice 
for students learning C programming and file management. 
